references: Now that we have stated the optimal server-side aggregation, we consider optimal learning strategies on the client side. In particular, we find that FedHDP achieves the Bayes optimal solution (Local Bayes obj.) for local estimates at both the private as well as the non-private clients when using the optimal value of the ratio hyperparameter r∗superscript𝑟r^{*} as well as the regularization parameters λjsubscript𝜆𝑗\lambda_{j}’s for each client. Lemma 3 in Appendix A.3 states the Bayes optimality of this solution and states the optimal values of each of the regularization parameters λj∗superscriptsubscript𝜆𝑗\lambda_{j}^{*}. It is worth mentioning that this result shows that FedHDP recovers the (Local Bayes obj.), which is the best one could hope for even if the client had access to DP versions of all other clients’ updates without any constraints that arise in FL, such as just having access to the global model. We also notice that the values of λ∗superscript𝜆\lambda^{*} are different for private and non-private clients. We recall that during the computation of the expressions for the personalization parameters for all clients we considered the presence of data heterogeneity as well as privacy heterogeneity. In Table 1 we provide a few important special cases for the FedHDP algorithm for the considered federated linear regression problem.
